# {{ isa_name }} — C++ ISA description headers

Header-only, standalone **C++17** (standard library only). These headers *describe*
the {{ isa_name }} instruction set so you can build a functional or cycle model on top —
they do not execute instructions or model state.

## Files

| Header | Contents |
|---|---|
| `{{ cls }}Enums.h` | `enum class Op` (one per instruction) + `mnemonic()`; `RegClass`; `Category`; `OperandKind` |
| `{{ cls }}InstrInfo.h` | `struct InstrInfo` / `OperandInfo` + `info(Op)` — opcode, mask/match, operands, category, exec_type, behavior string, latency |
| `{{ cls }}Decoder.h` | `decode(word) -> Op`, `get_bits()` / `sext()`, `decode_imm(op, word)` |
| `{{ cls }}Encoder.h` | `encode_<OP>(operands…) -> word`, one per instruction — the inverse of the decoder |
| `{{ cls }}.h` | umbrella include |
| `example_main.cpp` | a runnable example |

## Use

```cpp
#include "{{ cls }}.h"
using namespace {{ ns }};

Op op = decode(word);
const InstrInfo &i = info(op);

// Register operands: read the index out of the word using the field descriptor.
for (unsigned k = 0; k < i.num_operands; ++k) {
    const OperandInfo &o = i.operands[k];
    if (o.kind == OperandKind::Reg)
        unsigned idx = get_bits(word, o.start, o.width);   // e.g. gpr index
}

// Immediates (split fields and sign-extension handled for you):
int64_t imm = decode_imm(op, word);

// Cycle model: each instruction carries a latency from the uArch.
uint32_t cycles = i.latency;
```

The `latency` and `exec_type` fields come from the uArch manifest passed with
`--uarch`; without one, `latency` defaults to `1`.

## Regenerating

```sh
isa-archive generate --isa <isa>.yaml [--uarch <uarch>.yaml] -t cpp-isa -o build/cpp
```

Do not edit the generated headers by hand — regenerate from the manifests.
